      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "166e5eddc6f91af5",
      "text": "Robert Harrild was a successful printer whose company Harrild & Sons licensed the design for the [[Albion Press]] to manufacture them. The head London office was in Farringdon Road which is now a bar which remembers the company name. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "960587214697b46f",
      "text": "He lived in Round Hill House, [[Forest Hill]] at a time just before the railway acquired the [[Croydon Canal]]. As such he was well positioned financially and geographically to buy at auction and oversee the development of a plot on an extensive reservoir sold by the Canal company."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b694eeb0be2ddccd",
      "text": "The houses and roads he created left a small buffer area next to the railway to provide the genteel residents with a modest area of green which was never built on. One of his roads called Albion Villas Rd was named after the printing presses he manufactured under license. Today that patch of undeveloped land where he probably kept his deer, a 1.7 acre area is now [[Albion Millennium Green]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "48497d44a1e8925d",
      "text": "Robert Harrild clearly had a stong ability to value heritage he as aquired two remarkable trophies for posterity. One is [[St.Antholin's Spire]], an unusually solid stone spire of a church designed by [[Christopher Wren]] which is still in his old garden at Round Hill. The other was the [[Franklin Press]], which [[Benjamin Franklin]] had worked on in London. He safeguarded this knowing it's world historical significance. He exhibited it before presenting it to the American John Murray and it is now in the Smithsonian’s National Museum of American History, Washington. The money raised during it's exhibition before it was sent abroad was put to the London Printers' Pension Society to create a Franklin Pension Fund."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "771bb659635c6100",
      "text": "Near the very end of his life, he loaned the money to acquire land for the creation of the Kirkdale Institute. This would not be built until after he was dead, but realised a dream conceived by John Scott Russell and [[Joseph Paxton]] to provide a working men's institute for education.   "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4a4a8bc8697ff5c6",
      "text": "One of Robert Harrild's sons called Thomas is uncle (by marriage) to the celebrated pioneer nature writer [[Richard Jefferies]] who stayed with his aunt and uncle in a nearby house which is today commemorated with a plaque."
